    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. Restrict rows to only cmdb_id values that are in the candidate lists: os_001..os_022, docker_001..docker_008, db_001..db_013. For each group (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute and store in kernel an aggregated table with: count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, mean, P95, P90, P50 (median), and P5 of the 'value' column (use the full available series for each group). Return a compact JSON summary: total number of unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs, and a list of top 20 pairs by count with fields {cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, min_timestamp, max_timestamp, P95, P90, P50, P5}. Do NOT filter by the incident time window yet. Keep full aggregated table in kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing: aggregated each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) time series and stored the global thresholds (P95, P90, P50, P5) in the kernel variable agg_table. Next we must perform anomaly detection within the incident window (May 23, 2020 01:00–01:30, UTC+8) using these global thresholds. We have not yet extracted the incident-only metric points nor computed which component-KPI pairs breached their global thresholds during the incident window. Therefore we cannot identify faults or localize root cause yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and the previously stored agg_table from the kernel. Filter metric.csv to rows satisfying: cmdb_id in the candidate lists (os_001..os_022, docker_001..docker_008, db_001..db_013) AND timestamp within the incident window May 23, 2020 01:00 to 01:30 (UTC+8), inclusive. Store this filtered table in kernel variable incident_metrics. Then perform anomaly detection using agg_table thresholds: for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) present in incident_metrics, mark a data point as a high anomaly if value >= group's P95, or as a low anomaly if value <= group's P5. Aggregate anomalies by (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and produce a compact summary for up to top 20 pairs sorted by highest severity (see below) with fields: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, threshold_P95, threshold_P5, anomaly_type ('high' if max_value>=P95 else 'low'), max_severity. Define severity for high anomalies = (max_value - P95)/P95 if P95>0 else (max_value - P95); for low anomalies severity = (P5 - min_value)/P5 if P5>0 else (P5 - min_value). Return that compact JSON summary and keep incident_metrics and the anomalies aggregated table in kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed anomaly detection for the incident window and identified a large number of high-severity anomalies. The highest-severity anomalies are dominated by DB KPIs (Redo_Per_Sec, Logic_Read_Per_Sec, Physical_Read_Per_Sec) with extraordinarily large spikes (severity >> 50) and earliest anomaly timestamps at the start of the window (1590166800). Several OS disk KPIs also show strong anomalies (e.g., os_010 Disk_avgqu_sz, Disk_wr_ios, Page_po). According to the workflow, we must now perform fault identification by converting these anomalous points into consecutive anomaly sub-series (fault windows) to filter out isolated spikes. We should focus on DB KPIs (candidate root-cause resources) first because their deviations are most significant and likely indicate the root cause level. We have not yet identified consecutive fault windows (start/end times and lengths) for DB components, so we cannot yet finalize the root cause component or exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variable anomalies_rows (raw anomalous points), filter rows where cmdb_id starts with 'db_' and kpi_name is one of ['Redo_Per_Sec','Logic_Read_Per_Sec','Physical_Read_Per_Sec']. For each group (cmdb_id, kpi_name) sort by timestamp and detect consecutive anomaly sequences where adjacent timestamps differ by exactly 60 seconds. For each detected sequence produce a row with: cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_in_points, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (same as start_timestamp), max_value_in_sequence, min_value_in_sequence, threshold_P95, threshold_P5. Return up to top 20 sequences sorted by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Store the full sequences table in kernel variable faults_db for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, threshold calculation, incident filtering, anomaly detection, and DB fault identification. The Executor produced faults_db: consecutive anomaly sequences for DB components and the three DB KPIs. Key observations: many DBs (db_001..db_013) show high-severity, multi-point anomalies (Redo_Per_Sec, Logic_Read_Per_Sec, Physical_Read_Per_Sec) starting at the incident window start (1590166800). Some DB Physical_Read_Per_Sec sequences are long (e.g., db_011 length 30 covering the whole window), while Redo/Logic spikes are extremely large in magnitude on multiple DBs (severity >> 50). OS-level disk KPIs (e.g., os_010 Disk_avgqu_sz, os_001 Disk_await, os_018 Disk_rd_kbs/Page_pi) also showed strong anomalies at the same time. We still lack a consolidated view across OS, Docker, and DB levels to decide the root cause level/component. Traces available earlier cover docker and os_021/os_022 only and do not include db_*; thus trace-based downstream selection for DBs may not be possible. Next we should assemble fault sequences for OS and Docker components (from the already-detected anomalous points) and produce a compact per-component summary (counts, earliest start, severity, predominant KPIs) so we can compare levels (DB vs OS vs Docker) and pick the most likely root cause level and components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the kernel variable anomalies_rows (raw anomalous points), detect consecutive-60s anomaly sequences for components whose cmdb_id starts with 'os_' and 'docker_'. For each sequence produce: cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_in_points, max_value_in_sequence, min_value_in_sequence, threshold_P95, threshold_P5, and computed max_severity (use same severity formula as before). Store full sequences in kernel variables faults_os and faults_docker respectively. Then aggregate per component (cmdb_id) to produce a compact summary table with fields: cmdb_id, total_sequences, earliest_sequence_start, max_sequence_length, max_severity_over_sequences, top_3_kpis_by_sequence_count (as list). Return up to top 20 component summaries sorted by max_severity_over_sequences descending. Keep faults_os and faults_docker in kernel for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, incident filtering, anomaly detection, and fault identification. The Executor produced consecutive anomaly sequences for DB, OS, and Docker components and aggregated per-component summaries. Observations so far: many DB nodes show extremely large high-severity spikes in Redo/Logic/Physical read KPIs starting at the incident window start (1590166800). Multiple OS nodes also show persistent long sequences (length up to 30) with high severities; os_010 has the single largest-severity sequence (Disk_avgqu_sz severity≈367.7) beginning at 1590166800. Docker anomalies exist but are lower severity and shorter. According to the diagnosis rules, when different levels (node/container/service) show faults, the root-cause level is indicated by the fault with the most significant deviation from its threshold. We still need a compact, comparative per-level summary to decide the root-cause level and then pick the root-cause component among candidates at that level (use top severity and persistence to choose). Traces cover docker and a couple of OS nodes only (no db_* traces), so trace-based downstream selection for DBs is not possible. Logs are not available. Therefore the next step is to compute a concise per-level comparison and the top candidate components within each level to pick the most likely root-cause level and component.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel tables faults_db, faults_os, faults_docker, produce a compact comparative summary by level: for each level ('db','os','docker') compute and return: number_of_components_with_sequences, total_sequences_count, earliest_sequence_start (min start_timestamp), max_severity_over_level, median_severity_over_level, and the top 5 components (cmdb_id) sorted by max_severity with fields {cmdb_id, max_severity, earliest_sequence_start, max_sequence_length, total_sequences}. Limit returned rows to these aggregates only (JSON-serializable). Do not include raw time series. Store the level summary in kernel variable level_summary for next steps."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation, incident filtering, anomaly detection, and fault identification across DB, OS, and Docker levels. Aggregated level comparison (level_summary) shows: OS level has the single largest deviation (max_severity≈367.7) vs DB level max_severity≈236.9 and Docker max_severity≈1.0. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple levels show faults, the root-cause level should be the one with the most significant deviation from threshold. Therefore the OS level is the leading candidate. Within OS, os_010 is the top candidate (max_severity≈367.71, earliest_sequence_start=1590166800, persistent sequences up to 30 points) and its top KPI contributor appears to be Disk_avgqu_sz (very large severity), together with other disk-related KPIs (Disk_wr_ios, Page_po, Disk_await, Disk_svctm) showing persistent anomalies. DB KPIs also show severe spikes, but these are likely downstream effects of the OS-level disk problem. We should confirm os_010’s fault details (which KPIs, exact earliest anomalous timestamp, and concrete anomalous values) to lock the exact root-cause component and the occurrence time before finalizing the root cause reason. At this point the most plausible root-cause reason (given telemetry) is an OS disk I/O degradation; mapping to the permitted reason categories, this could be caused by \"network delay\" if storage is remote, but we need to confirm the KPI pattern on os_010 first.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Inspect os_010 details to confirm root cause: 1) From the kernel table faults_os, filter rows with cmdb_id == 'os_010' and return up to the top 10 sequences sorted by max_severity descending. For each sequence return fields: kpi_name, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_in_points, max_value_in_sequence, threshold_P95, threshold_P5, max_severity. 2) From the incident_metrics (or anomalies_rows) table, filter rows where cmdb_id == 'os_010' and kpi_name == 'Disk_avgqu_sz' and return up to the first 20 rows sorted by timestamp with fields: timestamp, value. Return results as compact JSON structures and keep filtered results in kernel for the final localization step."
}

{
    "analysis": "We followed the required workflow: computed global thresholds for all component-KPI series, filtered metrics to the incident window (May 23, 2020 01:00–01:30 UTC+8), detected anomalies, identified consecutive-fault sequences, and compared faults across levels. Results show severe, persistent OS-level disk I/O anomalies starting at the incident window start (timestamp 1590166800). os_010 has the single largest deviation from threshold (Disk_avgqu_sz severity ≈367.7, Disk_wr_ios severity ≈62.0, and a Page_po spike severity 112.0), beginning at 1590166800. Many DB nodes show very large downstream spikes in Redo/Logic/Physical read KPIs at the same time, consistent with storage I/O degradation impacting database performance. Traces do not include db_* services, so metric patterns must guide localization. By the rule that the root-cause level is the one with the most significant deviation when multiple levels are faulty, the OS level is selected and os_010 is the top component candidate. The telemetry points that define the root fault start at timestamp 1590166800 (the first anomalous point for os_010 Disk_avgqu_sz and other disk KPIs).",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Final diagnosis summary: Root cause component = os_010 (node-level). Root cause occurrence time = timestamp 1590166800 (start of the incident window; May 23, 2020 01:00 UTC+8). Root cause reason = suspected storage I/O latency (mapped to 'network delay' in the provided reason set) — evidence: extreme Disk_avgqu_sz spike on os_010 (severity ≈367.7), sustained high Disk_wr_ios and Page_po spikes on os_010, and simultaneous large DB KPI spikes (Redo_Per_Sec, Logic_Read_Per_Sec, Physical_Read_Per_Sec) consistent with downstream impact. Recommended immediate actions (operational): 1) Investigate os_010 disk subsystem and I/O queueing (check device latency, I/O scheduler, disk errors). 2) If storage is network-attached, check SAN/NAS/network connectivity and latency between os_010 and storage (network path, switch, storage health). 3) Correlate with storage/backend metrics and host logs (dmesg, iostat) to confirm disk errors or network storage latency. 4) Mitigate by throttling heavy I/O jobs or diverting workload and restoring storage performance. If you want, I can extract the exact raw anomalous metric rows for os_010 (limited rows) or fetch additional trace/log slices around 1590166800 for deeper confirmation."
}

